erefordshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England","Powick, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Powick, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1375–1465":"1375–1465","1361–1438":"1361–1438","1375–Male":"1375–Overleden","1379–Female":"1379–Overleden","1398–Male":"1398–Overleden","1332–1388":"1332–1388","1345–1411":"1345–1411","Bef 20 September 1388":"vóór 20 september 1388","2 September 1411":"2 september 1411","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1379":"1379","1455":"1455","1411":"1411","1345":"1345","1465":"1465","1388":"1388","1398":"1398","1332":"1332","1375":"1375","1438":"1438","Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England","Powick, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Powick, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1375–1465":"1375–1465","1361–1438":"1361–1438","1375–Male":"1375–Deceased","1379–Female":"1379–Deceased","1398–Male":"1398–Deceased","1332–1388":"1332–1388","1345–1411":"1345–1411","Bef 20 September 1388":"before 20 September 1388","2 September 1411":"2 September 1411","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1379":"1379","1455":"1455","1411":"1411","1345":"1345","1465":"1465","1388":"1388","1398":"1398","1332":"1332","1375":"1375","1438":"1438","Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Vowchurch, Herefordshire, England","Powick, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Powick, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bromwich","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from West Bromwich (Staffs) or Castle and Little Bromwich (Warwicks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Brommage","meanings":["English:  see  Bromwich  ."]},{"name":"Brumage","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Bromage  ."]},{"name":"Bromage","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Worcestershire): habitational name from West Bromwich in Staffordshire, or Castle and Little Bromwich in Warwickshire, named in Old English with <i>brōm</i> ‘broom’ (the shrub) + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying dairy farm’. Compare   Brumage  ."]},{"name":"Brimage","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Brumage  . This name is comparatively rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Bromige","meanings":["English:  see  Bromwich  ."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":80,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane de Bromwich was born in 1375, in Kent, England, her father, John de Bromwich Justiciar of Ireland, was 44 and her mother, Maude Elizabeth Porter, was 30. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Pye. She died in 1465, in Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1375–1465":"1375–1465","1361–1438":"1361–1438","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1379–Female":"1379–Surnud","1398–Male":"1398–Surnud","1332–1388":"1332–1388","1345–1411":"1345–1411","Bef 20 September 1388":"enne 20. se